# TESS Program G07178

Title: The Most Precise TESS Photometry For The Brightest Stars

PI: Huber, Daniel - University Of Hawaii (Manoa)

Type: SMALL

Summary: The most powerful tests of stellar structure and evolution come from the brightest stars in the sky. Recent results have shown that TESS 20-second cadence photometry yields strongly improved photometric precision per unit time compared to other observing modes. However, the stars that benefit the most from this improvement are frequently not observed with 20-second cadence. The key goal of this program is to ensure the best possible photometry of the brightest stars TESS observes. The software tools and data products produced in this program will enable numerous science applications, including the search for low amplitude oscillations in red giants and tests of stellar structure and evolution through pulsations in massive stars.
